1
00:00:18,286 --> 00:00:20,518
(HORSE TROTTING)

2
00:00:56,760 --> 00:00:59,025
(BELL RINGING)

3
00:01:20,320 --> 00:01:21,754
Mr. Blackwood?

4
00:01:25,590 --> 00:01:26,888
Sir?

5
00:01:31,030 --> 00:01:33,191
(GLASS SHATTERING)

6
00:01:35,768 --> 00:01:38,635
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

7
00:01:57,525 --> 00:01:59,857
Mr...

8
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:03,862
Mr. Blackwood, I'm sorry.
You did ring, sir?

9
00:02:04,532 --> 00:02:05,521
[BLACKWOOD]: Come down.

10
00:02:27,223 --> 00:02:28,554
(SCREAMS)

11
00:02:38,201 --> 00:02:39,897
(WHEN YOU AND I WERE YOUNG,
MAGGIE PLAYING)

12
00:02:40,003 --> 00:02:43,497
♪ I wandered today
to the hill, Maggie

13
00:02:45,676 --> 00:02:47,407
(GROANING)

14
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:51,813
♪ The creek and the creaking
old mill, Maggie

15
00:02:51,917 --> 00:02:53,179
I'm so...

16
00:02:53,386 --> 00:02:56,012
So very sorry.

17
00:02:57,189 --> 00:02:58,986
I didn't see the steps.

18
00:02:59,092 --> 00:03:00,389
They made me do it.

19
00:03:00,692 --> 00:03:01,682
I didn't...

20
00:03:04,096 --> 00:03:05,428
(GRUNTS)

21
00:03:06,065 --> 00:03:08,259
If I want to see
my child again,

22
00:03:09,636 --> 00:03:10,728
I must comply.

23
00:03:10,838 --> 00:03:11,930
Mr. Blackwood.

24
00:03:12,039 --> 00:03:13,370
Please understand.

25
00:03:16,310 --> 00:03:17,298
(GASPS)

26
00:03:18,511 --> 00:03:19,774
(WHIMPERS)

27
00:03:20,481 --> 00:03:21,449
(SCREAMING)

28
00:03:29,024 --> 00:03:30,012
(MUFFLED SCREAMS)

29
00:03:36,096 --> 00:03:41,501
♪ Are gone, Maggie
When you and I...

30
00:03:42,471 --> 00:03:45,336
[BLACKWOOD]: Precious teeth.
Beautiful teeth.

31
00:03:50,480 --> 00:03:51,880
Ransom for my boy.

32
00:03:55,151 --> 00:03:56,311
Yes.

33
00:04:03,228 --> 00:04:08,556
♪ They say I'm feeble
with age, Maggie

34
00:04:09,900 --> 00:04:11,368
[BOY FAINTLY]: Daddy.

35
00:04:13,738 --> 00:04:18,937
♪ My face is
a well written page, Maggie ♪

36
00:04:20,478 --> 00:04:21,501
(FAINT WHISPERING)

37
00:04:25,184 --> 00:04:27,276
(SNARLING)

38
00:04:30,689 --> 00:04:34,718
I... brought you something
more to eat.

39
00:04:36,296 --> 00:04:40,227
Not children's teeth
like you wanted,

40
00:04:41,067 --> 00:04:44,229
but please accept them...

41
00:04:45,170 --> 00:04:47,106
in exchange for him.

42
00:04:47,208 --> 00:04:49,936
CREATURES: Children's teeth.

43
00:04:50,043 --> 00:04:52,534
(CREATURES HISSING)

44
00:04:52,646 --> 00:04:54,944
Oh, no,
that's the best I could do.

45
00:04:55,148 --> 00:04:58,277
And they're my own.
You see?

46
00:04:59,052 --> 00:05:00,179
My own.

47
00:05:00,888 --> 00:05:04,551
(SOBBING) Please.
Give me back my son!

48
00:05:04,792 --> 00:05:09,127
CREATURES: Yes, your son is down here.
Reach for him.

49
00:05:09,364 --> 00:05:11,662
Son? Son!

50
00:05:11,766 --> 00:05:13,233
(BOY FAINTLY CALLING)

51
00:05:13,367 --> 00:05:14,335
Son!

52
00:05:15,336 --> 00:05:16,395
Grab my hand!

53
00:05:17,805 --> 00:05:19,034
(CREATURES SHRIEKING)

54
00:05:19,374 --> 00:05:21,866
(SCREAMING)

55
00:07:08,425 --> 00:07:10,359
(INTERCOM BEEPS)

56
00:07:10,460 --> 00:07:13,121
[FLIGHT ATTENDANT]: We've now begun
our descent into T. F. Green Airport.

57
00:07:13,328 --> 00:07:15,455
Please return to your seat,
make sure it is in...

58
00:07:15,498 --> 00:07:17,523
(CART BEEPING)

59
00:07:26,177 --> 00:07:27,201
She's landed.

60
00:07:28,713 --> 00:07:30,579
What do you think?
Too much?

61
00:07:30,682 --> 00:07:33,343
No, it's perfect.
Just like you.

62
00:07:33,452 --> 00:07:35,078
(CART HONKS)

63
00:07:35,420 --> 00:07:36,477
There's my girl.

64
00:07:37,656 --> 00:07:38,623
Sally?

65
00:07:39,525 --> 00:07:42,584
Wow! Look
how tall you are!

66
00:07:43,428 --> 00:07:44,589
What are you,
17 now?

67
00:07:44,697 --> 00:07:46,664
Dad, you know
how old I am.

68
00:07:46,765 --> 00:07:48,096
I know.
I'm being silly.

69
00:07:48,467 --> 00:07:49,730
Hey.
Good morning, sir.

70
00:07:50,770 --> 00:07:51,929
Thank you.

71
00:07:52,104 --> 00:07:53,129
[ALEX]: Come on.

72
00:07:53,873 --> 00:07:56,306
Sally, this is Kim.
Kim, Sally.

73
00:07:57,009 --> 00:07:58,806
Hi, Sally.
It's nice to meet you.

74
00:08:00,714 --> 00:08:02,977
[TOY BEAR]: I love you.
I love you.

75
00:08:03,584 --> 00:08:04,551
Thanks.

76
00:08:05,519 --> 00:08:07,820
What about a picture?
You got your camera?

77
00:08:09,054 --> 00:08:10,353
It's good
to see you.

78
00:08:13,561 --> 00:08:14,925
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

79
00:08:16,931 --> 00:08:19,058
[MAN ON RADIO]: Good morning,
Rhode Island!

80
00:08:19,267 --> 00:08:21,098
- [KIM]: Everything okay?
- [ALEX]: Yeah.

81
00:08:21,369 --> 00:08:24,361
We've got fog this morning and a
slight chance of a shower later on.

82
00:08:24,573 --> 00:08:25,800
Smell that fresh air,
kiddo?

83
00:08:26,074 --> 00:08:27,769
- Sure beats the smog of LA, huh?
- (WATCH ALARM RINGS)

84
00:08:37,018 --> 00:08:38,884
(DIALING PHONE)

85
00:08:39,155 --> 00:08:40,179
I have to call
Mom now.

86
00:08:41,157 --> 00:08:43,786
Just press one
and the green.

87
00:08:44,160 --> 00:08:46,492
(PHONE RINGING)

88
00:08:47,964 --> 00:08:52,402
Hi, you've called Joanne and
the magical Sally! Leave us a message.

89
00:09:29,209 --> 00:09:31,007
L.C. delivered
the flooring.

90
00:09:31,110 --> 00:09:33,170
If it rains,
I'm afraid it's gonna warp.

91
00:09:33,380 --> 00:09:35,244
Well, just put it
in the garage.

92
00:09:35,681 --> 00:09:37,548
Sally, say hello
to Mr. Harris.

93
00:09:40,321 --> 00:09:41,651
Nice to meet you.

94
00:09:44,291 --> 00:09:46,520
[ALEX]: Come,
take a look at the house.

95
00:09:50,331 --> 00:09:54,463
[MRS. UNDERHILL]: Mr. Harris. Mr. Harris,
would you give me a hand...

96
00:09:58,240 --> 00:10:00,765
- [KIM]: How's it going?
- Good.

97
00:10:01,910 --> 00:10:05,277
- When do you think you'll be finished?
- No problem.

98
00:10:34,712 --> 00:10:35,838
Good, huh?

99
00:10:39,416 --> 00:10:41,749
- It smells funny.
- You should've smelled it before.

100
00:10:41,853 --> 00:10:43,787
They had moldy
newspapers everywhere,

101
00:10:43,887 --> 00:10:45,879
and dead pigeons all over
the floor and poop.

102
00:10:45,990 --> 00:10:47,014
(PHONE RINGING)

103
00:10:47,125 --> 00:10:48,558
Lots of it.
It's Jacoby's office.

104
00:10:49,227 --> 00:10:50,421
Mr. Jacoby.

105
00:10:50,629 --> 00:10:52,357
Oh, hey, Michelle.
Sorry.

106
00:10:54,566 --> 00:10:57,297
Uh, I don't know.
Hold on. I'll check.

107
00:10:57,403 --> 00:10:59,099
You got the photographs?

108
00:11:21,395 --> 00:11:22,885
I like to draw, too.

109
00:11:28,102 --> 00:11:29,228
You work here?

110
00:11:30,403 --> 00:11:32,031
No, Sally,
I live here.

111
00:11:32,841 --> 00:11:35,900
I'm the interior designer.
Do you know what that is?

112
00:11:36,610 --> 00:11:37,907
Of course you do.

113
00:11:40,114 --> 00:11:42,710
You see all the animal
paintings and friezes?

114
00:11:42,818 --> 00:11:45,946
They're by Emerson Blackwood,
a man who once lived here.

115
00:11:46,755 --> 00:11:49,055
He was a very famous
wildlife painter.

116
00:11:51,393 --> 00:11:52,758
Hey, Sally, look.

117
00:11:55,632 --> 00:11:56,927
You want to try?

118
00:11:59,135 --> 00:12:00,432
What do you
have there?

119
00:12:01,705 --> 00:12:04,062
- I found it.
- That's mine.

120
00:12:06,275 --> 00:12:07,609
It was my grandmother's.

121
00:12:07,910 --> 00:12:10,010
When I was little,
my mother gave it to me.

122
00:12:10,614 --> 00:12:12,145
My mom gave me
to my dad.

123
00:12:12,783 --> 00:12:13,772
[ALEX]: Sally?

124
00:12:14,118 --> 00:12:15,984
You wanna see your room?

125
00:12:40,747 --> 00:12:42,043
What do you think?

126
00:12:43,250 --> 00:12:45,811
Kim and I worked really hard
to get it ready.

127
00:12:45,919 --> 00:12:47,546
Check this out.

128
00:12:49,423 --> 00:12:51,949
(LULLABY PLAYING)

129
00:12:52,059 --> 00:12:53,356
It's pretty great, huh?

130
00:12:56,095 --> 00:12:57,893
It looks better
at night.

131
00:13:02,436 --> 00:13:03,631
How long am I
staying here?

132
00:13:05,672 --> 00:13:07,607
What did your mother tell you?

133
00:13:07,943 --> 00:13:09,807
She told me
I was coming to visit.

134
00:13:09,978 --> 00:13:11,842
But then she packed
all my clothes.

135
00:13:12,915 --> 00:13:14,177
She didn't explain
anything to you?

136
00:13:15,550 --> 00:13:17,273
- No.
- Sally.

137
00:13:17,285 --> 00:13:19,244
Your mother and I
are worried about you.

138
00:13:19,254 --> 00:13:22,811
She thinks that maybe you're, uh...
feeling sad...

139
00:13:22,925 --> 00:13:25,519
and she thought that...
Well, we thought that...

140
00:13:25,720 --> 00:13:27,220
perhaps a... a change

141
00:13:27,230 --> 00:13:29,225
might... might be good for you
and that you could come

142
00:13:29,232 --> 00:13:30,899
and live here
with... with Kim and me...

143
00:13:30,999 --> 00:13:33,659
until we finish the work
on the house and... and sell it.

144
00:13:33,769 --> 00:13:36,304
And then, uh... we could move
somewhere else and...

145
00:13:38,576 --> 00:13:40,338
Sally? Come on.
Open the door.

146
00:13:44,215 --> 00:13:45,512
Come on.
Let me in.

147
00:13:48,086 --> 00:13:49,748
(SOBBING) Are you going
to marry her?

148
00:13:50,121 --> 00:13:51,087
(CHUCKLES)

149
00:13:52,524 --> 00:13:55,125
Uh... that's between
Kim and me.

150
00:13:55,327 --> 00:13:58,420
Mom said you only liked her
because she was young.

151
00:13:59,664 --> 00:14:02,965
But she isn't.
She is old.

152
00:14:02,966 --> 00:14:03,860
Sally.

153
00:14:04,402 --> 00:14:05,836
Open the door.

154
00:14:05,937 --> 00:14:08,030
Come on, sweetheart.
Open the door.

155
00:14:08,206 --> 00:14:10,334
Sally, please,
let's talk about this.

156
00:14:15,013 --> 00:14:16,311
Look, I know...

157
00:14:20,519 --> 00:14:21,818
I know it must
be tough.

158
00:14:21,921 --> 00:14:26,257
You had a long flight, and it's...
it's strange being in a new house.

159
00:14:26,258 --> 00:14:27,617
I wanna go to bed now.

160
00:14:31,030 --> 00:14:31,998
Okay.

161
00:14:39,307 --> 00:14:41,537
Don't forget to
brush your teeth.

162
00:14:59,861 --> 00:15:01,591
You'd be a terrible
poker player.

163
00:15:01,797 --> 00:15:04,130
You've been ironing that shirt
for like, half-an-hour.

164
00:15:07,905 --> 00:15:09,632
She sure didn't take to me.

165
00:15:10,873 --> 00:15:11,897
I wouldn't take
it personally.

166
00:15:12,007 --> 00:15:13,567
She's like that
with everybody.

167
00:15:13,677 --> 00:15:15,906
Those pills she takes,
what are they?

168
00:15:16,378 --> 00:15:17,504
Adderall, I think.

169
00:15:18,215 --> 00:15:19,341
Jesus.

170
00:15:19,549 --> 00:15:20,641
That's her mother
for you.

171
00:15:21,552 --> 00:15:23,348
That woman medicated
our dogs.

172
00:15:24,654 --> 00:15:25,622
(SOFT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING
ON STEREO)

173
00:15:27,058 --> 00:15:30,151
So, what about Jacoby?

174
00:15:31,363 --> 00:15:34,325
Well, his assistant said he still hasn't
looked at the new photographs yet.

175
00:15:34,433 --> 00:15:36,031
- He's had them for a week.
- I know.

176
00:15:36,033 --> 00:15:38,266
But we're still in the running,
and he's still coming to the dinner.

177
00:15:38,270 --> 00:15:40,499
- He should just give us the cover.
- Yes, he should.

178
00:15:40,504 --> 00:15:42,530
He gave it to the Spencer restoration
two years ago...

179
00:15:42,542 --> 00:15:44,342
and you have
done miracles here.

180
00:15:44,343 --> 00:15:47,707
We have done miracles here.
It's not all about me.

181
00:15:49,949 --> 00:15:51,007
Thank you.

182
00:15:52,517 --> 00:15:53,644
These are new?

183
00:15:54,053 --> 00:15:55,145
- Yeah.
- Great.

184
00:15:55,355 --> 00:15:57,488
Well, if we get the cover
of Architectural Digest,

185
00:15:57,489 --> 00:15:59,715
we won't need to take out
another bank loan, will we?

186
00:16:03,631 --> 00:16:05,532
You know what your daughter
told me today?

187
00:16:05,733 --> 00:16:06,699
What?

188
00:16:07,433 --> 00:16:09,664
She said your wife
gave her to you.

189
00:16:13,206 --> 00:16:15,903
Kids say all kinds of things
they don't mean.

190
00:16:19,780 --> 00:16:21,771
It couldn't have
gone any worse today.

191
00:16:22,716 --> 00:16:23,705
(SIGHS)

192
00:16:23,818 --> 00:16:25,877
I feel like
the evil stepmother.

193
00:16:26,588 --> 00:16:29,022
The evil
and very old stepmother.

194
00:16:29,125 --> 00:16:31,589
Let's not forget the old part.
(LAUGHING)

195
00:16:31,660 --> 00:16:35,351
'Cause I was kinda thinking
you were looking a little ancient.

196
00:16:35,464 --> 00:16:36,563
- [KIM]: Oh, yeah?
- Oh, yeah.

197
00:16:36,731 --> 00:16:38,790
The stuffed bear?
What was I thinking?

198
00:16:38,801 --> 00:16:41,293
Oh, come on. It's great.
She likes it. I saw it in her room.

199
00:16:41,303 --> 00:16:42,400
[KIM]: On her bed?

200
00:16:42,604 --> 00:16:45,641
Well, above the bed.
Hanging by a noose.

201
00:16:45,642 --> 00:16:46,642
(KIM CHUCKLES)

202
00:16:46,843 --> 00:16:49,206
That's okay. Nice sign
of affection, I think.

203
00:16:49,244 --> 00:16:51,780
(KIM'S LAUGH ECHOING)

204
00:16:53,449 --> 00:16:54,883
(LULLABY PLAYING)

205
00:17:05,830 --> 00:17:07,491
(SIGHS)

206
00:17:40,767 --> 00:17:45,795
[CREATURES WHISPERING]: Sally.
Her name is Sally.

207
00:17:51,545 --> 00:17:54,014
(HUMMING)

208
00:18:10,600 --> 00:18:11,567
Sally!

209
00:19:27,915 --> 00:19:29,212
(GASPS)

210
00:19:59,115 --> 00:20:00,082
[KIM]: What do you think?

211
00:20:00,849 --> 00:20:02,147
Yeah. Looks great.

212
00:20:03,820 --> 00:20:04,980
Have you seen Sally?

213
00:20:05,154 --> 00:20:06,349
Yeah, she's
on the bench.

214
00:20:08,825 --> 00:20:09,951
[ALEX]: Sally!

215
00:21:14,496 --> 00:21:16,725
(SCREAMING)

216
00:21:17,666 --> 00:21:19,361
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

217
00:21:20,701 --> 00:21:23,262
It is not safe
for you back here.

218
00:21:24,239 --> 00:21:26,706
Hey. What's going on?
Everything okay?

219
00:21:26,808 --> 00:21:28,470
Keep her out from
the back of the house.

220
00:21:28,578 --> 00:21:30,875
She could fall in.
We'd be in a hell of a mess.

221
00:21:30,981 --> 00:21:32,709
I didn't do anything.

222
00:21:32,915 --> 00:21:35,008
There's pits.
Old wells.

223
00:21:35,118 --> 00:21:36,784
It's dangerous
for a child.

224
00:21:36,786 --> 00:21:38,584
Mr. Harris is right,
Sally. He knows.

225
00:21:38,653 --> 00:21:39,853
His grandfather
worked at the house.

226
00:21:39,855 --> 00:21:42,024
- You shouldn't be back here.
- But I found a basement.

227
00:21:42,025 --> 00:21:43,325
There is no basement.

228
00:21:43,426 --> 00:21:45,523
Easy, Harris.
I'll take her. It's okay.

229
00:21:47,331 --> 00:21:49,859
It's there!
It's right there!

230
00:21:54,005 --> 00:21:57,331
You know there's a reason
this house is called Fallen Mill.

231
00:21:57,641 --> 00:22:00,401
The English had a mill here,
and it fell into a sinkhole.

232
00:22:00,478 --> 00:22:02,845
That's why most of the houses
around here don't have basements.

233
00:22:02,947 --> 00:22:03,874
This one does.

234
00:22:04,181 --> 00:22:05,642
[ALEX]: You may wanna
check this out.

235
00:22:05,951 --> 00:22:07,278
[HARRIS]:
It's unsafe for a child.

236
00:22:07,284 --> 00:22:08,174
Pull on that.

237
00:22:09,387 --> 00:22:10,352
(ALEX LAUGHS)

238
00:22:10,356 --> 00:22:12,280
[SALLY]: Look!
I told you it was here!

239
00:22:12,290 --> 00:22:13,388
[ALEX]: Can you believe this?

240
00:22:17,596 --> 00:22:18,995
(KNOCKING)

241
00:22:20,734 --> 00:22:22,191
This is
definitely hollow.

242
00:22:23,635 --> 00:22:24,933
I'm gonna get some tools.

243
00:22:29,909 --> 00:22:31,371
You sure
you wanna do this now?

244
00:22:31,444 --> 00:22:32,841
Of course!
You kidding?

245
00:22:32,846 --> 00:22:34,843
We can fix this easy
if we have to.

246
00:22:34,947 --> 00:22:36,641
You may wanna
step back.

247
00:22:37,985 --> 00:22:40,352
(HAMMERING)

248
00:22:41,322 --> 00:22:42,519
[HARRIS]: Mr. Hurst, I...

249
00:22:45,694 --> 00:22:47,923
(ALEX GRUNTING)

250
00:23:00,541 --> 00:23:01,839
There's a door in here.

251
00:23:06,382 --> 00:23:07,979
Where did you put
the old house keys?

252
00:23:08,284 --> 00:23:10,513
They're in your junk drawer
in the office.

253
00:23:10,686 --> 00:23:11,711
Okay.

254
00:23:12,757 --> 00:23:14,053
Have a look.

255
00:23:43,988 --> 00:23:45,222
[ALEX]: Oh, wow.

256
00:23:46,123 --> 00:23:47,386
You be careful, Sally.

257
00:23:47,387 --> 00:23:48,587
Okay?
Okay.

258
00:23:51,396 --> 00:23:52,963
How the hell
did we miss this?

259
00:23:59,072 --> 00:24:00,598
[KIM]: That must be
the garden window.

260
00:24:09,750 --> 00:24:11,878
[KIM]: It's all of his paints
and old colored pencils.

261
00:24:11,879 --> 00:24:13,179
This is amazing.

262
00:24:29,636 --> 00:24:31,836
Wow.
Alex, look at this.

263
00:24:39,981 --> 00:24:41,381
Harris, did you know
about this?

264
00:24:41,483 --> 00:24:43,748
This place isn't safe.
(STAMMERS)

265
00:24:43,854 --> 00:24:45,744
Especially for kids.

266
00:24:45,755 --> 00:24:46,920
It's okay.
I'll keep an eye on her.

267
00:24:49,091 --> 00:24:50,992
This must be
where Blackwood worked.

268
00:24:51,294 --> 00:24:52,654
[SALLY]:
I found another door.

269
00:24:53,162 --> 00:24:54,491
[KIM]:
Look at these sketches.

270
00:24:54,564 --> 00:24:55,791
It's an ash pit,
I think.

271
00:24:56,700 --> 00:24:59,129
Yeah.
It's bolted shut.

272
00:24:59,736 --> 00:25:01,551
[KIM]:
These are incredible.

273
00:25:05,643 --> 00:25:07,685
(GASPS)

274
00:25:07,743 --> 00:25:10,052
[ALEX]: Okay.
Let's go, Sally.

275
00:25:20,490 --> 00:25:22,235
Come on, Sally.
Let's go.

276
00:25:23,192 --> 00:25:24,709
[ALEX]: Sally, come on.

277
00:25:26,195 --> 00:25:28,531
This must be like
King Tut's tomb for you.

278
00:25:28,532 --> 00:25:30,968
[KIM]: Which is excatly why
we shouldn't be touching anything.

279
00:25:30,969 --> 00:25:32,501
This stuff must
be valuable.

280
00:25:32,502 --> 00:25:34,205
[CREATURES HISSING]:
She's gone.

281
00:25:34,206 --> 00:25:35,937
No, no, she will come back.

282
00:25:35,938 --> 00:25:37,839
They always do.

283
00:25:37,840 --> 00:25:40,726
Yes, they always do.

284
00:26:16,581 --> 00:26:18,622
[ALEX]: I don't think
that's important, Alan.

285
00:26:20,049 --> 00:26:21,750
No, I just need
to make sure I get

286
00:26:21,751 --> 00:26:24,635
the paintings and furniture
back in time for the dinner.

287
00:26:25,055 --> 00:26:26,802
You told me
you could.

288
00:26:28,259 --> 00:26:29,792
Come on. How long
have we known each other?

289
00:26:29,793 --> 00:26:32,108
I'll write you
a post-dated check.

290
00:26:34,263 --> 00:26:35,679
Hold on.

291
00:26:36,365 --> 00:26:41,583
It's either walnut or mahogany,
I think. Yeah.

292
00:26:42,172 --> 00:26:43,880
Hey, there you are.

293
00:26:44,281 --> 00:26:46,681
I thought maybe
we could bake scones.

294
00:26:46,943 --> 00:26:49,713
I promised Mrs. Underhill
we wouldn't make too much of a mess.

295
00:26:50,614 --> 00:26:52,260
No. That's all right.

296
00:26:53,683 --> 00:26:55,061
What've you got there?

297
00:26:57,387 --> 00:27:00,228
My doll.
And my drawing stuff.

298
00:27:06,797 --> 00:27:10,246
[KIM]: Looks like it's just you and I
baking scones today.

299
00:27:17,006 --> 00:27:19,550
[MRS. UNDERHILL]:
I made sandwiches for everyone.

300
00:27:48,071 --> 00:27:50,751
(GRUNTING)

301
00:28:02,285 --> 00:28:04,135
[CREATURES WHISPERING]:
Sally.

302
00:28:04,255 --> 00:28:06,187
Open the grates!

303
00:28:06,188 --> 00:28:08,023
Yes, yes,
open the grates.

304
00:28:08,024 --> 00:28:11,567
Set us free!
Set us free!

305
00:28:15,497 --> 00:28:17,245
Who are you?

306
00:28:18,133 --> 00:28:19,881
What do you look like?

307
00:28:19,903 --> 00:28:23,072
We've been locked
up for so long.

308
00:28:23,073 --> 00:28:25,286
Set us free!

309
00:28:26,509 --> 00:28:27,926
(GASPS)

310
00:28:28,744 --> 00:28:32,560
Come down. You'll see
what it's like down here.

311
00:28:32,615 --> 00:28:33,949
Wait a minute, will ya?

312
00:28:33,950 --> 00:28:38,437
There's other children down here.
They're just like you.

313
00:28:40,456 --> 00:28:41,900
[ALEX]: Sally?

314
00:28:46,396 --> 00:28:47,813
Sally.

315
00:28:49,566 --> 00:28:51,274
What're you doing down here?

316
00:28:53,102 --> 00:28:55,022
- I heard something.
- Rats, probably.

317
00:28:55,223 --> 00:28:56,723
Come on,
it's time for dinner.

318
00:28:56,972 --> 00:28:58,206
It was a voice.

319
00:28:58,207 --> 00:28:59,408
Really smart rats, then.

320
00:28:59,409 --> 00:29:01,383
No! Listen.

321
00:29:17,593 --> 00:29:20,076
Nothing.
Come on, let's go, kiddo.

322
00:29:34,443 --> 00:29:35,877
I forgot my bag.

323
00:29:35,878 --> 00:29:37,422
Well, hurry up.

324
00:29:53,930 --> 00:29:56,109
(CLANKING)

325
00:30:04,308 --> 00:30:06,140
(GASPS)

326
00:30:06,141 --> 00:30:07,956
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

327
00:30:55,926 --> 00:30:57,471
[ALEX]: Sally, now!

328
00:31:33,462 --> 00:31:34,363
We can get this tomorrow.

329
00:31:34,364 --> 00:31:36,063
We can't get the rest of these
for two weeks.

330
00:31:36,064 --> 00:31:37,833
What about
the burnt umber?

331
00:31:37,834 --> 00:31:40,281
It's much warmer, and we can get it
for half he price.

332
00:31:41,770 --> 00:31:44,189
You not hungry?
Sally?

333
00:31:46,643 --> 00:31:47,989
Don't you like rice?

334
00:31:49,144 --> 00:31:51,488
Mrs. Underhill
made apple pie for dessert.

335
00:31:52,316 --> 00:31:53,815
Apple pie has gluten,

336
00:31:53,816 --> 00:31:55,815
and Mommy says gluten is bad
for my concentration.

337
00:31:55,816 --> 00:31:57,853
Oh, come on.
You love apple pie.

338
00:31:57,854 --> 00:32:00,154
We can worry about your
concentration tomorrow.

339
00:32:00,655 --> 00:32:02,335
Mommy says no gluten.

340
00:32:02,992 --> 00:32:04,493
What's your mother
filling your head with?

341
00:32:04,494 --> 00:32:06,094
- How about some chocolate milk?
- No, no, no.

342
00:32:06,095 --> 00:32:07,496
- I'll make something else.
- No. Hold on, hold on.

343
00:32:07,497 --> 00:32:08,563
Sally,
you need to eat this,

344
00:32:08,564 --> 00:32:10,709
or you can go to your room.
Okay?

345
00:32:12,167 --> 00:32:13,447
Good night, Dad.

346
00:32:21,377 --> 00:32:22,584
What?

347
00:32:23,378 --> 00:32:24,780
Did that work on you
when you were a kid?

348
00:32:24,781 --> 00:32:25,880
She's testing us, Kim.

349
00:32:25,881 --> 00:32:28,717
That's what kids do.
Who's the parent here?

350
00:32:28,718 --> 00:32:30,552
Certainly not me.

351
00:32:30,553 --> 00:32:32,086
I didn't... mean that.

352
00:32:32,087 --> 00:32:35,190
No... You're right.
I'm not a parent.

353
00:32:35,191 --> 00:32:38,603
- We talked about this, remember?
- No, you told me about this, Alex.

354
00:32:39,161 --> 00:32:41,740
I'm not sure I'm ready
to be anybody's mother.

355
00:32:41,741 --> 00:32:43,597
- Oh, come on.
- I had a hard enough time...

356
00:32:43,598 --> 00:32:44,999
getting over my own childhood...

357
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:46,868
to have to...
deal with somebody else's.

358
00:32:46,869 --> 00:32:48,637
Listen, will you help me
out with this, please?

359
00:32:48,638 --> 00:32:51,171
I realize this is terrible timing,
but I don't have a choice.

360
00:32:51,172 --> 00:32:52,884
I can't...
I can't just send her back.

361
00:32:55,712 --> 00:32:57,952
You know, that's not
what I'm asking you to do.

362
00:33:05,221 --> 00:33:06,268
Apple pie.

363
00:33:07,257 --> 00:33:08,396
Thanks.

364
00:33:18,268 --> 00:33:20,148
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

365
00:33:22,404 --> 00:33:24,589
- Hello?
- Hi, Alex, it's Joanne.

366
00:33:24,740 --> 00:33:26,374
- Hi, Joanne.
- Can I speak to Sally?

367
00:33:26,375 --> 00:33:27,860
- No, you can't.
- Why not?

368
00:33:28,011 --> 00:33:30,896
Because she's asleep.
We're 3 hours ahead, remember?

369
00:33:30,947 --> 00:33:32,247
What were you thinking
not telling her...

370
00:33:32,248 --> 00:33:33,529
she was gonna be living here?

371
00:33:39,622 --> 00:33:40,724
You and I had a conversation.

372
00:33:40,725 --> 00:33:43,175
I asked you
if you wanted me to tell her.

373
00:33:43,525 --> 00:33:45,026
Don't do this
every time I have...

374
00:33:45,027 --> 00:33:46,676
You're the one
who wanted her here.

375
00:33:56,538 --> 00:33:58,456
(GASPS)

376
00:34:36,747 --> 00:34:39,220
(LULLABY PLAYING)

377
00:34:43,251 --> 00:34:46,802
- [TOY BEAR]: I love you. I love you.
- (GASPS)

378
00:34:53,594 --> 00:34:57,214
Did... did you just
speak to me?

379
00:34:57,265 --> 00:35:01,083
I love you.
I love you.

380
00:35:02,105 --> 00:35:04,112
I love you.

381
00:35:04,674 --> 00:35:06,420
I love you.

382
00:35:07,776 --> 00:35:09,558
I love you.

383
00:35:10,948 --> 00:35:12,494
I love you.

384
00:35:17,954 --> 00:35:20,065
(SCREAMS)

385
00:35:20,621 --> 00:35:22,490
(CREATURES SHRIEKING)

386
00:35:22,491 --> 00:35:24,726
[CREATURES]: The light,
it hurts us.

387
00:35:24,727 --> 00:35:26,575
Yeah. Turn out the light.

388
00:35:27,864 --> 00:35:29,611
I love you.

389
00:35:30,133 --> 00:35:32,601
(CREATURES WHISPERING)

390
00:35:32,602 --> 00:35:34,644
Turn out the light.

391
00:35:35,103 --> 00:35:37,851
We want to be friends.

392
00:35:43,410 --> 00:35:44,378
Where's my doll?

393
00:35:44,379 --> 00:35:46,263
[CREATURES WHISPERING]:
With us. With us.

394
00:35:46,314 --> 00:35:48,364
Sally's doll is with us.

395
00:35:50,018 --> 00:35:51,702
Who are you?

396
00:35:51,754 --> 00:35:53,702
We're your friends.

397
00:35:56,892 --> 00:35:58,239
Friends?

398
00:36:00,195 --> 00:36:01,413
Where?

399
00:36:01,497 --> 00:36:03,632
[CREATURES WHISPERING]:
Come down to the basement...

400
00:36:03,633 --> 00:36:05,283
- and play with us.
- Where are you?

401
00:36:22,284 --> 00:36:23,531
What are you?

402
00:36:33,061 --> 00:36:34,604
[CREATURES]: Hungry.

403
00:36:34,863 --> 00:36:36,080
Hungry.

404
00:36:36,832 --> 00:36:38,648
Very hungry.

405
00:36:40,135 --> 00:36:42,280
(WHISPERS)
I have food.

406
00:36:48,610 --> 00:36:50,292
Let me see you.

407
00:36:51,246 --> 00:36:53,264
I won't hurt you,
I promise.

408
00:36:55,383 --> 00:36:56,500
[ALEX]: Sally?

409
00:36:58,221 --> 00:37:00,472
- What you doing under there?
- I'm looking for my doll.

410
00:37:01,123 --> 00:37:02,273
Looking for what?

411
00:37:02,524 --> 00:37:04,002
I'm looking for my doll.

412
00:37:04,059 --> 00:37:05,176
[ALEX]: Oh.

413
00:37:09,364 --> 00:37:10,464
Well, uh...
Oh.

414
00:37:10,465 --> 00:37:12,900
How about, the...
Teddy instead?

415
00:37:12,901 --> 00:37:14,579
- No.
- I love you.

416
00:37:14,830 --> 00:37:15,980
That's all right.

417
00:37:18,572 --> 00:37:20,823
- Did you lose a tooth?
- That's not mine.

418
00:37:21,309 --> 00:37:22,937
- I found it.
- You found it?

419
00:37:22,938 --> 00:37:24,288
What?
Here in the house?

420
00:37:25,613 --> 00:37:26,660
Yeah.

421
00:37:26,911 --> 00:37:27,961
Come on.

422
00:37:29,318 --> 00:37:30,902
Can I call Mommy now?

423
00:37:30,953 --> 00:37:33,454
No, it's too late.
She's probably asleep.

424
00:37:33,455 --> 00:37:36,334
I don't think you should keep this.
It's not very sanitary.

425
00:37:37,592 --> 00:37:39,175
What about this light?
Should I...

426
00:37:39,695 --> 00:37:40,942
Leave it on, please.

427
00:37:41,664 --> 00:37:43,644
All right, well,
sleep well.

428
00:37:46,434 --> 00:37:49,246
Oh, Sally,
would you do me a favor?

429
00:37:50,272 --> 00:37:52,815
Would you try to,
maybe, be friends with Kim?

430
00:37:55,144 --> 00:37:56,918
- Yes.
- Thanks, kiddo.

431
00:38:26,609 --> 00:38:28,321
(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING
ON STEREO)

432
00:38:30,313 --> 00:38:32,230
Kim, have you seen
my razor?

433
00:38:32,980 --> 00:38:34,514
We have to leave
in five minutes.

434
00:38:34,515 --> 00:38:37,264
- Yeah. You seen my razor?
- Here, take mine.

435
00:38:37,720 --> 00:38:38,926
Five minutes.

436
00:38:50,932 --> 00:38:52,150
My dress.

437
00:39:02,911 --> 00:39:04,852
(HUMMING)

438
00:39:15,758 --> 00:39:19,066
Sally. I wanna talk to you
downstairs right now.

439
00:39:23,998 --> 00:39:26,033
[ALEX]: I cannot believe
you cut up Kim's clothes.

440
00:39:26,034 --> 00:39:27,301
- [SALLY]: I didn't do it.
- Sally...

441
00:39:27,302 --> 00:39:28,397
- I didn't do anything.
- Sally...

442
00:39:28,398 --> 00:39:30,048
- I swear.
- Stop lying.

443
00:39:30,805 --> 00:39:33,007
It was a horrible thing to do.
And it was dangerous.

444
00:39:33,008 --> 00:39:34,241
You could've cut yourself.

445
00:39:34,242 --> 00:39:35,989
What did you use,
my razor?

446
00:39:36,012 --> 00:39:37,654
Let me see
your hands.

447
00:39:37,845 --> 00:39:39,446
- It's mine.
- What is this?

448
00:39:39,447 --> 00:39:40,493
Where'd you get this?

449
00:39:42,216 --> 00:39:44,017
- Let me go home.
- You can't go home.

450
00:39:44,018 --> 00:39:45,235
Just let me go home.

451
00:39:46,788 --> 00:39:48,039
I'm sorry about this.

452
00:39:48,290 --> 00:39:49,723
She's never done
anything like this before.

453
00:39:49,724 --> 00:39:52,192
She's obviously very
angry about something.

454
00:39:52,193 --> 00:39:54,945
Alex, that is not anger.
That is fear.

455
00:39:55,096 --> 00:39:56,848
We need to go.
Mrs. Underhill,

456
00:39:57,099 --> 00:39:59,166
Kim and I have an appointment
at the historical society.

457
00:39:59,167 --> 00:40:00,651
We'll be back
this afternoon.

458
00:40:01,102 --> 00:40:02,986
Sally, we're going out.

459
00:40:03,239 --> 00:40:05,589
You listen to Mrs. Underhill
and do what she says.

460
00:40:05,740 --> 00:40:08,418
And you think about
what you need to say to Kim, okay?

461
00:40:24,660 --> 00:40:28,566
(FAINT WHISPERING)

462
00:40:35,570 --> 00:40:37,317
Are you there?

463
00:40:48,484 --> 00:40:50,662
Did you cut
Kim's clothes?

464
00:40:57,092 --> 00:40:59,373
Do you have
my dad's razor?

465
00:41:01,497 --> 00:41:03,674
You have to tell me
the truth.

466
00:41:04,666 --> 00:41:06,444
If you wanna be friends.

467
00:41:09,471 --> 00:41:11,119
I won't be angry.

468
00:41:12,240 --> 00:41:14,921
[CREATURE 1 WHISPERING]:
Sally's not angry.

469
00:41:15,044 --> 00:41:17,177
[CREATURE 1]:
They're angry.

470
00:41:17,178 --> 00:41:20,061
[CREATURE 2]:
No, I'm not angry.

471
00:41:20,548 --> 00:41:23,583
[CREATURE 1]:
They don't want to...

472
00:41:23,584 --> 00:41:25,002
[CREATURES]:
But we do.

473
00:41:27,456 --> 00:41:30,305
[CREATURES]:
Come down here, Sally.

474
00:41:30,658 --> 00:41:33,941
Come down and play.

475
00:41:38,500 --> 00:41:40,567
(CREATURES SCREECHING)

476
00:41:40,568 --> 00:41:43,112
(HISSING)

477
00:41:45,540 --> 00:41:47,718
You said you
were hungry.

478
00:41:47,976 --> 00:41:50,223
Do you like raisins?

479
00:41:55,416 --> 00:41:57,459
[CREATURES]:
We said we liked them.

480
00:42:02,724 --> 00:42:05,641
See? Delicious.

481
00:42:05,895 --> 00:42:09,263
Delicious. Yeah.

482
00:42:09,264 --> 00:42:12,081
So delicious.

483
00:42:13,768 --> 00:42:15,810
Did you do
something bad?

484
00:42:16,905 --> 00:42:19,506
You have to answer
if you wanna be friends.

485
00:42:19,507 --> 00:42:21,456
[CREATURES]:
Yes, friend.

486
00:42:21,743 --> 00:42:23,557
Sally?

487
00:42:24,712 --> 00:42:27,123
What're you doing
down here in the dark?

488
00:42:30,050 --> 00:42:32,593
Were you talking
to someone?

489
00:42:34,521 --> 00:42:36,599
Is there someone
here with you?

490
00:42:37,458 --> 00:42:40,538
No. I'm all alone.

491
00:42:41,063 --> 00:42:42,979
There's nobody here.

492
00:42:44,097 --> 00:42:49,850
Why don't you go help
Mrs. Underhill make lunch?

493
00:42:51,573 --> 00:42:53,207
Go on.
Off you go now.

494
00:42:53,208 --> 00:42:56,683
That's right. Up those steps!
Quick as you can, now!

495
00:43:49,030 --> 00:43:51,039
(GRUNTS)

496
00:43:55,135 --> 00:43:57,917
[CREATURES WHISPERING]:
Harris. You old fool.

497
00:43:59,641 --> 00:44:02,219
(CREATURES WHISPERING)

498
00:44:02,944 --> 00:44:06,955
[HARRIS]: I swear.
I didn't tell them anything!

499
00:44:21,229 --> 00:44:23,738
(SCREAMING)

500
00:44:28,770 --> 00:44:30,187
(HISSING)

501
00:44:33,141 --> 00:44:34,558
(GROANING)

502
00:44:38,545 --> 00:44:39,963
No.

503
00:44:42,150 --> 00:44:43,566
(YELLING)

504
00:44:45,887 --> 00:44:48,066
No, please!

505
00:44:49,223 --> 00:44:50,639
(CREATURES SHRIEKING)

506
00:44:53,494 --> 00:44:54,910
(GROANING)

507
00:45:02,170 --> 00:45:03,587
(SCREECHING)

508
00:45:10,045 --> 00:45:11,790
Get away!

509
00:45:12,112 --> 00:45:16,000
I had an accident!
Call for help!

510
00:45:18,119 --> 00:45:19,534
(COUGHING)

511
00:45:24,624 --> 00:45:27,306
(MOANING)

512
00:45:32,033 --> 00:45:33,450
(GRUNTING)

513
00:45:43,878 --> 00:45:45,294
Oh.

514
00:45:45,612 --> 00:45:47,358
Don't look.

515
00:45:48,148 --> 00:45:49,565
(SOBBING)

516
00:45:52,719 --> 00:45:55,156
[MRS. UNDERHILL]: I could hear
screams down there.

517
00:45:55,157 --> 00:45:56,958
- Noises.
- [COP]: Did you see anything?

518
00:45:56,959 --> 00:45:58,759
[MRS. UNDERHILL]:
He asked me to leave the cellar.

519
00:45:58,760 --> 00:46:00,927
It was so dark in there,
he must have stumbled.

520
00:46:00,928 --> 00:46:02,895
- Oh, Mr. Hurst, thank God!
- What happened?

521
00:46:02,896 --> 00:46:04,798
- Are you William Harris' employer?
- Yeah.

522
00:46:04,799 --> 00:46:05,999
There's been an accident.

523
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:07,900
Are you okay?
Where is Sally?

524
00:46:07,901 --> 00:46:10,337
I'm sorry.
She saw him.

525
00:46:10,338 --> 00:46:12,471
I tried to cover her eyes,
and I was too late.

526
00:46:12,472 --> 00:46:14,306
- Where is she?
- She's in the garden.

527
00:46:14,307 --> 00:46:16,053
(CRYING)
Oh, I am sorry!

528
00:46:18,211 --> 00:46:20,060
Sally?

529
00:46:38,599 --> 00:46:40,175
Hi.

530
00:46:42,837 --> 00:46:44,583
Are you scared?

531
00:46:47,575 --> 00:46:49,322
Do you wanna talk about it?

532
00:46:52,013 --> 00:46:54,431
Is Mr. Harris
gonna die?

533
00:46:56,017 --> 00:46:57,594
No, Sally.

534
00:46:58,351 --> 00:47:00,428
He is going
to be okay.

535
00:47:13,300 --> 00:47:15,240
Can I show you something?

536
00:47:48,236 --> 00:47:50,836
This is my favorite
part of the house.

537
00:47:50,837 --> 00:47:52,812
Blackwood loved nature.

538
00:47:53,607 --> 00:47:57,518
He imported these fish from Japan.
And so did we.

539
00:47:58,846 --> 00:48:00,593
They're called Koi.

540
00:48:01,415 --> 00:48:03,593
They're considered magical.

541
00:48:04,118 --> 00:48:07,236
Badgers can spot them
against the mud at the bottom...

542
00:48:07,287 --> 00:48:09,037
because of their
bright colors.

543
00:48:09,789 --> 00:48:12,326
So what makes them
special...

544
00:48:13,027 --> 00:48:16,173
is also what makes them
vulnerable.

545
00:48:16,731 --> 00:48:18,406
They have to be tough.

546
00:48:20,333 --> 00:48:21,851
And you, too, Sally.

547
00:48:26,306 --> 00:48:28,122
(CRYING)
I didn't touch your clothes.

548
00:48:31,210 --> 00:48:33,556
I swear to God,
I never touched them!

549
00:48:35,750 --> 00:48:38,049
- I didn't touch them.
- Sally.

550
00:48:38,050 --> 00:48:42,022
I didn't!
Didn't cut them, I promise.

551
00:48:42,023 --> 00:48:44,702
I don't care
about my clothes.

552
00:48:49,897 --> 00:48:52,513
[ALEX]: I can't really tell.
1804, I think.

553
00:48:53,134 --> 00:48:56,012
It's hard to see.
The coin's pretty worn down.

554
00:49:00,408 --> 00:49:02,451
She probably found it
in Blackwood's studio.

555
00:49:03,310 --> 00:49:05,411
[ALEX]: I don't want her
going down there anymore.

556
00:49:05,912 --> 00:49:08,832
I'm worried about her, Kim.
It's not safe.

557
00:49:15,458 --> 00:49:19,075
(PHONE DIALING)

558
00:49:19,493 --> 00:49:21,360
- Hey. This is Joanne.
- Mommy?

559
00:49:21,361 --> 00:49:24,340
Oh, sweetie, it's you!
How are you?

560
00:49:24,665 --> 00:49:26,134
Can I come home?

561
00:49:26,335 --> 00:49:29,434
- You wanna come home...
- The sashimi. Stuart, the sashimi.

562
00:49:29,435 --> 00:49:31,238
- I don't like it here.
- You what?

563
00:49:31,839 --> 00:49:34,807
Honey, don't fret.
It's so beautiful there.

564
00:49:34,808 --> 00:49:36,775
You just need
to get used to it.

565
00:49:36,776 --> 00:49:38,011
But it's cold.

566
00:49:38,512 --> 00:49:40,847
- Huh, Honey, what?
- My bed is too big.

567
00:49:40,948 --> 00:49:43,083
- Sweetheart.
- And I think I'm getting sick.

568
00:49:43,084 --> 00:49:44,884
You're not getting sick.

569
00:49:44,885 --> 00:49:47,186
Honey, it will take a little tiny bit
of getting used to,

570
00:49:47,187 --> 00:49:49,623
but you are gonna be
so happy there.

571
00:49:49,624 --> 00:49:53,266
Okay? I promise.
You'll get used to it.

572
00:49:54,228 --> 00:49:56,462
I gotta go, honey.
Mommy's gotta go.

573
00:49:56,463 --> 00:49:59,381
I'll see you soon. Bye!

574
00:50:25,157 --> 00:50:26,574
(LULLABY PLAYING)

575
00:50:55,889 --> 00:50:57,307
Kim?

576
00:51:06,667 --> 00:51:09,084
- Don't leave.
- What's wrong?

577
00:51:10,203 --> 00:51:12,281
Even when I'm asleep.

578
00:51:15,210 --> 00:51:17,183
And don't turn off
the lights.

579
00:51:19,747 --> 00:51:21,494
I'll be right here.

580
00:51:23,450 --> 00:51:24,959
Come on.

581
00:51:36,663 --> 00:51:39,513
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

582
00:52:39,293 --> 00:52:41,677
(CREATURES WHISPERING)

583
00:52:43,664 --> 00:52:45,081
(SCREECHING)

584
00:52:49,136 --> 00:52:50,609
Kim?

585
00:52:55,708 --> 00:52:58,525
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

586
00:53:01,680 --> 00:53:04,597
[TOY BEAR]: I love you.
I love you.

587
00:53:45,190 --> 00:53:47,292
(SHRIEKS)

588
00:53:47,293 --> 00:53:50,474
(SCREAMING)

589
00:53:52,565 --> 00:53:53,983
(GASPING)

590
00:53:54,534 --> 00:53:57,042
(CREATURES SCREECHING)

591
00:53:59,473 --> 00:54:00,889
(SCREAMING)

592
00:54:02,508 --> 00:54:05,019
Daddy! Daddy!

593
00:54:05,845 --> 00:54:07,394
Daddy, please!

594
00:54:07,981 --> 00:54:09,098
Daddy!

595
00:54:10,583 --> 00:54:12,716
Sally, what's the matter?
What's the matter?

596
00:54:13,017 --> 00:54:15,833
(SALLY SOBBING)

597
00:54:19,460 --> 00:54:21,328
I don't want them
to come anymore.

598
00:54:21,829 --> 00:54:23,145
Who, Sally?

599
00:54:23,697 --> 00:54:25,237
The little things.

600
00:54:26,199 --> 00:54:29,174
They live in the basement.
They gave me the silver dollar.

601
00:54:29,703 --> 00:54:31,505
They said they wanted to be
my friend.

602
00:54:31,706 --> 00:54:34,541
But they're horrible
and mean.

603
00:54:34,542 --> 00:54:36,016
Oh, Sally.

604
00:54:37,212 --> 00:54:39,810
- You just had a nightmare.
- No, don't say that!

605
00:54:40,747 --> 00:54:42,289
It's okay.

606
00:54:42,381 --> 00:54:43,799
(LULLABY PLAYING)

607
00:54:44,083 --> 00:54:45,659
My bear.

608
00:54:46,387 --> 00:54:48,032
Look what they did
to my bear.

609
00:55:19,052 --> 00:55:21,505
Your dad tells me
art is your favorite subject.

610
00:55:22,156 --> 00:55:23,706
I wish I could draw.

611
00:55:24,525 --> 00:55:26,533
Drawing is easy.

612
00:55:27,827 --> 00:55:30,246
The other kids
can't do feet and hands.

613
00:55:30,431 --> 00:55:34,416
When you say "the other kids",
do you feel they're different from you?

614
00:55:34,667 --> 00:55:36,435
My doctor back home
asked me that.

615
00:55:36,436 --> 00:55:38,546
What was your answer?

616
00:55:41,641 --> 00:55:45,925
Okay. Let's start
with something easier.

617
00:55:46,612 --> 00:55:48,087
What's your favorite color?

618
00:55:49,781 --> 00:55:51,030
What is that?
Purple?

619
00:55:52,118 --> 00:55:53,436
Black.

620
00:55:54,855 --> 00:55:58,907
How about these little things you saw?
What do you think they are?

621
00:56:05,933 --> 00:56:07,678
Fairies.

622
00:56:08,835 --> 00:56:10,402
Or gnomes.

623
00:56:10,403 --> 00:56:11,981
But scary ones?

624
00:56:14,807 --> 00:56:16,918
And you say they
know your name?

625
00:56:22,349 --> 00:56:23,925
They talk to you?

626
00:56:24,918 --> 00:56:26,335
Yes.

627
00:56:29,722 --> 00:56:31,468
What do they say?

628
00:56:32,893 --> 00:56:34,810
They want to play
with me.

629
00:56:34,927 --> 00:56:36,674
Is that all?

630
00:56:41,167 --> 00:56:43,608
They say my parents
don't love me.

631
00:56:47,206 --> 00:56:48,940
Can I go now?

632
00:56:48,941 --> 00:56:51,188
[PSYCHIATRIST]: Just a few
more questions, okay?

633
00:57:09,228 --> 00:57:11,812
There is a lot of anxiety
in that little girl...

634
00:57:11,863 --> 00:57:14,299
and a deep belief,
that she's not wanted.

635
00:57:14,300 --> 00:57:17,553
I believe that's what's triggering
these fantastic episodes.

636
00:57:18,304 --> 00:57:20,073
She told me
she found a little tray...

637
00:57:20,074 --> 00:57:22,175
filled with teeth
right inside that fireplace.

638
00:57:22,176 --> 00:57:25,760
Yeah. She found a tooth, but
that doesn't mean anything, does it?

639
00:57:25,813 --> 00:57:28,013
She's constructing
this elaborate fantasy...

640
00:57:28,014 --> 00:57:31,017
about wrinkles,
claws, fangs.

641
00:57:31,018 --> 00:57:33,502
Now she's individuated
each one of those things,

642
00:57:33,753 --> 00:57:35,587
her imaginary world,
its inhabitants.

643
00:57:35,588 --> 00:57:38,737
It's as detailed as any
I've ever encountered.

644
00:57:39,491 --> 00:57:40,958
What do we do?

645
00:57:40,959 --> 00:57:43,328
I'd like to try her on a stronger
medication, for a start.

646
00:57:43,329 --> 00:57:45,630
I'll ask her doctor in L.A.
to send me a copy of her charts.

647
00:57:45,631 --> 00:57:47,066
You call my office,
make another appointment.

648
00:57:47,067 --> 00:57:48,384
Okay, great.

649
00:57:48,435 --> 00:57:50,845
Meanwhile, I'll give you something
to help her sleep.

650
00:57:52,239 --> 00:57:54,816
(HORNS BLARING)

651
00:57:58,211 --> 00:58:00,645
I'm going to be late.
I can't believe it.

652
00:58:00,646 --> 00:58:02,046
If we don't get the extension
on this loan,

653
00:58:02,047 --> 00:58:03,582
we're not gonna get
the paintings or the furniture...

654
00:58:03,583 --> 00:58:04,701
back on time.

655
00:58:05,552 --> 00:58:06,718
(GROANS)

656
00:58:06,719 --> 00:58:09,018
We forgot the invitations
for the historical society.

657
00:58:09,019 --> 00:58:12,656
Maybe we should just
postpone the dinner.

658
00:58:12,657 --> 00:58:14,359
Kim,
it's Architectural Digest.

659
00:58:14,360 --> 00:58:16,027
We have to get
the house on the cover.

660
00:58:16,028 --> 00:58:16,930
- I know.
- If we don't,

661
00:58:16,931 --> 00:58:18,463
I'm never gonna get
my career back,

662
00:58:18,464 --> 00:58:19,666
and we're not gonna
sell the place.

663
00:58:19,667 --> 00:58:21,000
- How often we've talked about this?
- What about whats...

664
00:58:21,001 --> 00:58:22,084
been happening?

665
00:58:22,235 --> 00:58:23,701
What, Harris?
That was an accident.

666
00:58:23,702 --> 00:58:25,437
I'm talking about Sally.
These things...

667
00:58:25,438 --> 00:58:27,805
- It's all in her head!
- Yeah, but it's real to her.

668
00:58:27,806 --> 00:58:29,373
It doesn't matter
if we see it.

669
00:58:29,374 --> 00:58:30,442
- (HONKING)
- Come on!

670
00:58:30,443 --> 00:58:31,990
Calm down!

671
00:58:33,446 --> 00:58:37,023
I'm gonna walk. It'll be faster.
I'll see you back at home.

672
00:59:00,574 --> 00:59:03,275
I'm not sure
how lucid he'll be.

673
00:59:03,276 --> 00:59:05,284
He's pretty
heavily sedated.

674
00:59:06,578 --> 00:59:10,088
(MONITOR BEEPING)

675
00:59:37,075 --> 00:59:40,290
Mr. Harris,
I know this is difficult,

676
00:59:40,580 --> 00:59:43,296
but I need to
understand something.

677
00:59:43,583 --> 00:59:46,935
I need to know what Sally saw
so that I can help her.

678
00:59:48,054 --> 00:59:52,497
Is she out
of the house?

679
00:59:52,960 --> 00:59:54,377
No.

680
00:59:56,461 --> 00:59:57,970
Out.

681
00:59:58,465 --> 01:00:01,972
She needs to be
out of there.

682
01:00:03,903 --> 01:00:05,376
Why?

683
01:00:08,941 --> 01:00:11,360
Why was that
room sealed up?

684
01:00:14,413 --> 01:00:16,815
Grandfather.

685
01:00:16,816 --> 01:00:20,218
Your grandfather
closed it up?

686
01:00:20,219 --> 01:00:22,194
Yes.
Why?

687
01:00:23,822 --> 01:00:25,331
After...

688
01:00:26,926 --> 01:00:28,343
After...

689
01:00:31,663 --> 01:00:33,274
After what?

690
01:00:35,033 --> 01:00:36,507
Blackwood.

691
01:00:38,671 --> 01:00:40,486
What about Blackwood?

692
01:00:42,643 --> 01:00:47,892
Lot 1134.

693
01:00:48,649 --> 01:00:50,862
Public library.

694
01:00:52,417 --> 01:00:56,669
[HARRIS]: Get her
out of our house.

695
01:00:58,823 --> 01:01:01,765
(SKITTERING)

696
01:01:25,252 --> 01:01:28,670
[WOMAN ON PA]: The library
will be closing in 15 minutes.

697
01:01:28,721 --> 01:01:33,504
The library will be closing
in 15 minutes. Thank you.

698
01:01:35,062 --> 01:01:36,535
Excuse me.

699
01:01:37,897 --> 01:01:39,064
Can I help you?

700
01:01:39,065 --> 01:01:40,504
I'm looking for
the librarian.

701
01:01:42,967 --> 01:01:44,406
Lot 1134.

702
01:01:46,339 --> 01:01:49,386
Emerson Blackwood,
Special Collections. One sec.

703
01:01:55,114 --> 01:01:56,260
Right this way.

704
01:02:15,334 --> 01:02:17,436
Can't remember the last time
anyone requested these.

705
01:02:17,437 --> 01:02:19,436
- They're beautiful.
- I'm a designer.

706
01:02:19,437 --> 01:02:21,072
I've been working
at Fallen Mill.

707
01:02:21,273 --> 01:02:23,522
Wow.
Now, that's a privilege.

708
01:02:24,441 --> 01:02:27,891
Personally, I think
Emerson Blackwood rivaled Audubon.

709
01:02:29,014 --> 01:02:30,061
Come across his mural?

710
01:02:31,218 --> 01:02:32,385
A mural?
Where?

711
01:02:32,786 --> 01:02:34,554
There in the house,
supposedly.

712
01:02:35,155 --> 01:02:36,498
If you do,
I'd love to see it.

713
01:02:37,956 --> 01:02:41,204
(SALLY HUMMING)

714
01:03:12,058 --> 01:03:13,275
Hello?

715
01:03:32,678 --> 01:03:36,481
Now, it's pretty ironic,
really.

716
01:03:36,882 --> 01:03:38,182
For a committed realist,

717
01:03:38,183 --> 01:03:41,120
someone who insisted
on drawing only from nature,

718
01:03:41,521 --> 01:03:43,588
to do these
at the end of his life.

719
01:03:43,589 --> 01:03:45,023
I've looked at everything
by Blackwood,

720
01:03:45,024 --> 01:03:46,524
and I've never
seen any of these.

721
01:03:46,525 --> 01:03:49,259
Oh, you wouldn't. The family made it
a restricted donation.

722
01:03:49,460 --> 01:03:51,028
These may never
be published.

723
01:03:51,029 --> 01:03:52,605
Is it possible
to get copies?

724
01:03:53,732 --> 01:03:55,867
I'll see what I can do.

725
01:03:55,868 --> 01:03:58,684
"Wrinkles, claws,
teeth?"

726
01:03:59,139 --> 01:04:01,171
Have you ever
read Machen?

727
01:04:01,172 --> 01:04:03,420
Arthur Machen. Welsh.

728
01:04:03,443 --> 01:04:04,842
He believed
in fairy folk,

729
01:04:05,043 --> 01:04:07,415
these ancient entities
from the netherworld,

730
01:04:07,416 --> 01:04:08,816
predating mankind.

731
01:04:09,516 --> 01:04:11,549
Blackwood
quotes him extensively.

732
01:04:11,950 --> 01:04:13,818
Here, uh... that line.
There.

733
01:04:14,019 --> 01:04:15,719
"One life
must be taken".

734
01:04:15,920 --> 01:04:17,921
These creatures had to take
one human life...

735
01:04:17,922 --> 01:04:20,492
every time they emerged
to replenish their ranks.

736
01:04:20,793 --> 01:04:23,094
Many of these creatures
fed on the bones,

737
01:04:23,095 --> 01:04:25,063
the teeth
of young children.

738
01:04:25,464 --> 01:04:28,300
And then there's a... a truce,
a pact of sorts,

739
01:04:28,401 --> 01:04:30,870
between Pope Sylvester the 2nd
and these ancient beings...

740
01:04:30,871 --> 01:04:32,683
in the year 9 hundred
and 99.

741
01:04:33,539 --> 01:04:34,906
In exchange
for human teeth,

742
01:04:35,107 --> 01:04:37,891
they start leaving
silver pieces under the pillow.

743
01:04:44,749 --> 01:04:49,229
Now, this... is the last known
drawing by Emerson Blackwood,

744
01:04:49,955 --> 01:04:53,973
made shortly before his disappearance
and the loss of his child.

745
01:04:54,593 --> 01:04:55,695
His child?

746
01:04:56,096 --> 01:04:58,630
Blackwood's only son
vanished, lost.

747
01:04:59,131 --> 01:05:01,043
Not long after,
Blackwood himself disappeared...

748
01:05:01,944 --> 01:05:02,944
without a trace.

749
01:05:27,926 --> 01:05:28,943
No!

750
01:05:29,727 --> 01:05:31,940
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

751
01:05:38,069 --> 01:05:39,918
(SALLY SCREAMS)
(CREATURE SHRIEKS)

752
01:05:41,174 --> 01:05:43,487
(HISSING)

753
01:05:45,578 --> 01:05:47,120
(SALLY SCREAMING)

754
01:05:52,085 --> 01:05:54,558
(SNARLING)

755
01:05:58,089 --> 01:05:59,256
(GASPING)

756
01:05:59,257 --> 01:06:00,558
(SCREECHING)

757
01:06:00,559 --> 01:06:01,960
(SNARLING)

758
01:06:01,961 --> 01:06:03,329
No!

759
01:06:03,330 --> 01:06:06,077
No! Please!

760
01:06:06,098 --> 01:06:07,514
(SCREAMING)

761
01:06:11,669 --> 01:06:13,086
(SNARLING)

762
01:06:17,575 --> 01:06:18,993
(SCREAMING)

763
01:06:20,913 --> 01:06:22,624
[SALLY]: No!

764
01:06:31,858 --> 01:06:34,069
(SALLY SCREAMING)

765
01:06:36,327 --> 01:06:37,829
Sally!

766
01:06:37,830 --> 01:06:39,712
Sally, what's wrong?

767
01:06:40,264 --> 01:06:42,510
Sally, open the door!

768
01:06:43,402 --> 01:06:44,841
(GROWLING)

769
01:06:45,236 --> 01:06:47,120
(CRYING)

770
01:06:48,007 --> 01:06:49,719
(SNARLS)

771
01:06:50,042 --> 01:06:51,458
(SCREECHING)

772
01:06:52,311 --> 01:06:54,058
Oh, my God!

773
01:06:56,680 --> 01:06:58,950
Oh, oh.

774
01:06:58,951 --> 01:07:00,767
(PANICKED BREATHING)
Shh.

775
01:07:06,591 --> 01:07:08,959
(BREATHING RAPIDLY) Dear,
thank goodness you're home.

776
01:07:08,960 --> 01:07:11,528
Where is she?
I put her to bed.

777
01:07:11,529 --> 01:07:13,674
She wouldn't
stop screaming.

778
01:07:25,044 --> 01:07:26,619
Sally?

779
01:07:51,503 --> 01:07:52,920
(GRUNTS)

780
01:07:54,373 --> 01:07:56,984
(CHILD FAINTLY CRYING)

781
01:08:08,519 --> 01:08:09,493
[ALEX]: Kim!

782
01:08:10,488 --> 01:08:11,823
She's not down here.

783
01:08:12,024 --> 01:08:14,542
I think she's run away.
She's done it before.

784
01:08:17,162 --> 01:08:19,130
[ALEX]: You know, once she tried
to walk all the way back to L.A...

785
01:08:19,131 --> 01:08:20,431
from our family home
in Boston.

786
01:08:21,032 --> 01:08:24,368
I wouldn't be surprised
if that's what she's doing.

787
01:08:24,369 --> 01:08:26,411
(SIGHS)

788
01:08:34,113 --> 01:08:36,530
I went and visited
Harris today.

789
01:08:37,816 --> 01:08:40,184
Blackwood had a son.
Did you know that?

790
01:08:40,185 --> 01:08:42,519
And when he was eight,
he disappeared.

791
01:08:42,520 --> 01:08:44,487
And Blackwood vanished
a few days later.

792
01:08:44,488 --> 01:08:46,324
Why are you
telling me this?

793
01:08:46,325 --> 01:08:48,493
A lot of what Blackwood wrote
at the end of his life,

794
01:08:48,494 --> 01:08:50,728
it's awfully close
to Sally's story,

795
01:08:50,729 --> 01:08:52,563
gnomes, creatures,
all of it.

796
01:08:52,564 --> 01:08:54,066
Kim, don't tell me
you believe this.

797
01:08:54,067 --> 01:08:56,607
Something terrible happened
in that basement.

798
01:08:56,733 --> 01:08:58,002
We need to leave.

799
01:08:58,003 --> 01:08:59,503
- Put a million miles between...
- What're you talking about?

800
01:08:59,603 --> 01:09:01,438
- us and that house.
- Every cent I have...

801
01:09:01,439 --> 01:09:02,907
is in that house. Okay?
And you're saying...

802
01:09:02,908 --> 01:09:04,307
that we just walk away?

803
01:09:04,308 --> 01:09:07,477
Look, I... I accept
that my daughter has problems, okay?

804
01:09:07,478 --> 01:09:09,413
Thank you.
We all know that.

805
01:09:09,414 --> 01:09:11,727
But they do not involve
monsters in the basement.

806
01:09:12,751 --> 01:09:13,698
There she is.

807
01:09:29,234 --> 01:09:30,646
Come on, Sally.
Get in the car.

808
01:09:35,407 --> 01:09:37,574
Sally, please,
just tonight,

809
01:09:37,575 --> 01:09:39,416
after the party
we'll talk, okay?

810
01:10:04,202 --> 01:10:06,904
Four, three,

811
01:10:06,905 --> 01:10:09,749
two and one.

812
01:10:11,109 --> 01:10:12,027
There.

813
01:10:14,246 --> 01:10:16,715
After the party,
I will get you outta here.

814
01:10:17,116 --> 01:10:18,693
No matter what.
I promise.

815
01:10:25,590 --> 01:10:27,058
- Sally!
- No.

816
01:10:27,559 --> 01:10:28,892
I took it from them.

817
01:10:29,093 --> 01:10:30,629
- You can't have this.
- They stoled it.

818
01:10:30,930 --> 01:10:32,730
You don't understand.
I need it to fight back.

819
01:10:32,930 --> 01:10:34,596
- Absolutely not.
- Please!

820
01:10:37,669 --> 01:10:39,245
[SALLY]: Nobody believes me.

821
01:10:42,007 --> 01:10:44,249
Sally, I trust you,

822
01:10:45,109 --> 01:10:48,588
and you can tell me anything,
anything at all.

823
01:10:53,684 --> 01:10:55,764
They don't like
bright lights either.

824
01:10:57,755 --> 01:10:59,032
These things.

825
01:10:59,757 --> 01:11:00,675
They don't?

826
01:11:05,796 --> 01:11:07,143
Then I have a good idea.

827
01:11:13,137 --> 01:11:14,839
Mr. Jacoby, I am so glad
you could make it.

828
01:11:14,840 --> 01:11:16,873
- Alex, call me Charles.
- Charles.

829
01:11:16,874 --> 01:11:18,374
- My wife, Evelyn.
- Hello, Alex.

830
01:11:18,375 --> 01:11:19,976
It's a pleasure.
Come on in.

831
01:11:20,177 --> 01:11:23,080
The house looks
absolutely fantastic.

832
01:11:23,881 --> 01:11:25,382
You done
a remarkable job.

833
01:11:25,383 --> 01:11:27,384
Well, thank you.

834
01:11:27,785 --> 01:11:28,853
We'd love
the nickel tour.

835
01:11:28,954 --> 01:11:30,586
Of course.
That's the whole point.

836
01:11:30,887 --> 01:11:32,556
The foyer, obviously.

837
01:11:32,557 --> 01:11:34,792
The, uh, the mahogany, we shipped
from the very same vendor...

838
01:11:34,793 --> 01:11:36,126
that Blackwood
used in London.

839
01:11:36,227 --> 01:11:38,763
It's been in business
since 1865.

840
01:11:38,764 --> 01:11:40,866
You know Bill from the...
heritage board.

841
01:11:41,867 --> 01:11:45,081
Easy, Sally. Not everybody wants to have
their photograph taken, okay?

842
01:12:01,820 --> 01:12:03,187
So, Alex,
where's Kim?

843
01:12:03,288 --> 01:12:05,088
Uh... I think she's still
upstairs.

844
01:12:05,089 --> 01:12:07,025
Why don't you step into the library,
grab a drink,

845
01:12:07,026 --> 01:12:08,975
and I'll, uh...
I join you there in a moment.

846
01:12:11,463 --> 01:12:13,880
(ALL CHATTING)

847
01:12:19,204 --> 01:12:21,917
(CREATURES WHISPERING)

848
01:12:29,947 --> 01:12:31,728
(SHRIEKS)

849
01:12:34,886 --> 01:12:37,297
Kim, hey,
what's going on?

850
01:12:37,922 --> 01:12:40,697
Her drawings. They're exactly
Blackwood's sketches.

851
01:12:41,258 --> 01:12:44,027
Yeah, I'm sure she probably saw
your photographs and copied them.

852
01:12:44,094 --> 01:12:45,461
No, she didn't.

853
01:12:45,762 --> 01:12:47,431
Kim, please,
Jacoby's here.

854
01:12:48,032 --> 01:12:51,368
- Alex, this is your daughter!
- I know.

855
01:12:51,369 --> 01:12:52,636
This is serious!

856
01:12:53,537 --> 01:12:55,971
Just because you keep
denying it does not mean...

857
01:12:55,972 --> 01:12:57,673
- it's not happening.
- Kim, I can't do...

858
01:12:57,674 --> 01:12:59,309
Excuse me, Mr. Hurst.

859
01:12:59,310 --> 01:13:01,878
- When should we serve dinner?
- Ten minutes, please.

860
01:13:01,879 --> 01:13:04,116
Kim, everybody is waiting.
Will you come downstairs?

861
01:13:04,117 --> 01:13:06,160
- We can talk about this later.
- No.

862
01:13:19,964 --> 01:13:21,731
- I have proof, Dad. Look!
- Not now, honey.

863
01:13:21,732 --> 01:13:23,080
- Please!
- Not now. Come on!

864
01:13:27,838 --> 01:13:29,020
Welcome, everybody.

865
01:13:30,375 --> 01:13:31,915
Please, have a seat.

866
01:13:34,646 --> 01:13:36,680
Uh... if I could just say
a few words...

867
01:13:36,681 --> 01:13:38,848
to all of you friends
of Fallen Mill,

868
01:13:38,849 --> 01:13:40,516
both big and small.

869
01:13:40,517 --> 01:13:42,819
Um... thank you
for joining us this evening.

870
01:13:43,220 --> 01:13:44,669
It means
a great deal to us.

871
01:13:45,524 --> 01:13:50,293
Every aspect of this restoration, um...
has followed the exact specifications...

872
01:13:50,294 --> 01:13:53,329
and materials used in the original
construction of the house, um...

873
01:13:53,430 --> 01:13:57,335
including the wood assembling
techniques, the layout in the kitchen,

874
01:13:57,336 --> 01:14:00,170
even the, uh... lacquering process
for all the timber.

875
01:14:00,571 --> 01:14:03,540
It's something Kim and I
are very proud of, I'm sure all of you,

876
01:14:03,541 --> 01:14:06,409
with your vast array
of expertise, will, uh...

877
01:14:06,410 --> 01:14:08,462
appreciate
the attention to detail.

878
01:14:09,114 --> 01:14:12,248
Um... the art you see on the walls,
the friezes,

879
01:14:12,249 --> 01:14:15,152
even the furniture
that you're sitting on,

880
01:14:15,153 --> 01:14:19,556
uh, has all been meticulously chosen,
reassembled or restored,

881
01:14:19,557 --> 01:14:21,190
depending on its condition,

882
01:14:21,391 --> 01:14:25,763
uh, to, I think, truly represent
the essence of the Blackwood collection.

883
01:14:25,964 --> 01:14:28,232
Uh... so, thank you
to the heritage board...

884
01:14:28,333 --> 01:14:31,680
for their assistance,
and to the historical society too.

885
01:14:31,881 --> 01:14:32,781
Um...

886
01:14:34,003 --> 01:14:36,653
and of course, to our guest of honor,
Charles Jacoby.

887
01:14:36,654 --> 01:14:37,654
Your, uh...

888
01:14:37,874 --> 01:14:40,210
your interest
in our projects, um...

889
01:14:40,211 --> 01:14:43,053
is nothing short of inspirational.
So, thank you.

890
01:14:43,714 --> 01:14:46,249
And, uh... finally,
to the house itself.

891
01:14:46,450 --> 01:14:49,486
May its newly restored life
be long and happy.

892
01:14:49,687 --> 01:14:52,571
(ALL APPLAUDING)

893
01:14:56,160 --> 01:14:59,062
I guess not everybody is a fan
of tonight's menu.

894
01:14:59,063 --> 01:15:00,538
(ALL LAUGHING)

895
01:15:10,709 --> 01:15:12,455
(GASPS)

896
01:15:19,582 --> 01:15:21,295
(SHRIEKS)

897
01:15:24,356 --> 01:15:28,036
[CREATURES]: Poor Sally.
No one believes you.

898
01:15:32,831 --> 01:15:35,406
(CREATURES LAUGHING)

899
